04896nam a22007935i 9780812204681DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20122009pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013950686  a(OCoLC)979622869  a97808122046817 a10.9783/97808122046812doi  a(DE-B1597)449438  a(OCoLC)794702354  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBT741.3 -- M56 2009eb 7aREL0150002bisacsh04a235.21 aMiller, Patricia Cox, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Corporeal Imagination :bSignifying the Holy in Late Ancient Christianity /cPatricia Cox Miller. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2012] 4cÂ©2009  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b13 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDivinations: Rereading Late Ancient Religion00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One. Bodies and Selves -- tChapter Two. Bodies in Fragments -- tChapter Three. Dazzling Bodies -- tChapter Four. Bodies and Spectacles -- tChapter Five. Ambiguous Bodies -- tChapter Six. Subtle Bodies -- tChapter Seven. Animated Bodies and Icons -- tChapter Eight. Saintly Bodies as Image-Flesh -- tChapter Nine. Incongruous Bodies -- tConclusion -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith few exceptions, the scholarship on religion in late antiquity has emphasized its tendencies toward transcendence, abstraction, and spirit at the expense of matter. In The Corporeal Imagination, Patricia Cox Miller argues instead that ancient Christianity took a material turn between the fourth and seventh centuries. During this period, Miller contends, there occurred a major shift in the ways in which the human being was oriented in relation to the divine, a shift that reconfigured the relationship between materiality and meaning in a positive direction.The Corporeal Imagination is a groundbreaking investigation into the theological poetics of material substance in late ancient Christian texts. From hagiographies to literary descriptions of sacred paintings to treatises on relics and theurgy, Miller examines a wide variety of ancient texts to reveal how Christian writers increasingly described the matter of the world as invested with divine power. By appealing to the reader's sensory imagination, Christian texts endowed phenomena like relics, saints' bodies in hagiography, and saints' presence in icons with a visual and tactile presence. The book draws on a variety of contemporary theoretical models to elucidate the significance of all these materials in ancient religious life and imagination.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHuman bodyvReligious aspectsvChristianity. 0aHuman bodyxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 4aReligious Studies. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / History.2bisacsh  aAncient Studies.  aReligion.  aReligious Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Religionz978311041358808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220468140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812204681423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812204681.jpg  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Complete Collection  a978-3-11-041358-8  Penn Press eBook Package Religion  a978-3-11-045954-8  University of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL 